00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.639
about how this business transition is actually going to look like in practice.

00:03:41.839 --> 00:03:46.320
So let me start by just setting the scene a little bit for what I'm talking about.

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:51.839
Phil kind of alluded to this already, but Rush is obviously a really big company,

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:54.960
and today we're not here talking for the whole of Rush.

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:59.679
All of us are from a particular department at Rush called PD Data Sciences.

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:03.119
If you don't know what that is, that's fine.

00:04:03.119 --> 00:04:04.960
I'll explain it a little bit now.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:08.080
Our basic job is to report clinical trials.

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:15.119
So Rush obviously conducts loads of different clinical trials all over the world to gather

00:04:15.119 --> 00:04:21.440
data on the effectiveness of the different products we create to help fight diseases.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.239
And our role in PD Data Sciences is to make sure all that data is gathered accurately,

00:04:28.239 --> 00:04:34.799
following the protocols we've set out, and to summarize it so that we have a good picture

00:04:34.799 --> 00:04:36.239
of how these drugs work.

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:40.320
So as you might imagine, this is a really important job.

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:46.320
It's really vital that we get this right, that we have the safety and efficacy data

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:51.119
to be accurate, and that we can share it with regulators as soon as possible.

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:57.519
Because the more quickly we get this data summarized and presented,

00:04:57.519 --> 00:05:02.000
the quicker we can get drugs to patients to help them fight illnesses.

00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:06.799
So what's our goal then?

00:05:07.519 --> 00:05:14.959
So fundamentally, our goal in PD Data Sciences is to shift towards a language-agnostic framework.

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:22.399
And what I mean by that is we're moving away from having one solution for how we do our

00:05:22.399 --> 00:05:24.239
programming for clinical trials.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:29.679
We want the ability to be flexible and move towards the best language for solving our

00:05:29.679 --> 00:05:30.559
problems.

00:05:30.559 --> 00:05:36.480
And our expectation is that in future, there won't be necessarily one solution for solving

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:36.559
it.

00:05:36.559 --> 00:05:39.760
We'll be picking the best problem from the marketplace.

00:05:40.959 --> 00:05:46.160
So most of what we're talking about today is the first step on this journey, but we

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:49.359
will be alluding to the wider ideas of this as well.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:54.079
And that first step, I think, has already been mentioned a bit in the advertising for

00:05:54.079 --> 00:06:01.679
this seminar, which is that this year, from quarter two, novel studies will be using R

00:06:01.679 --> 00:06:03.679
as their core data science tool.

00:06:03.679 --> 00:06:06.799
So we'll be analyzing our data using R primarily.

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:10.399
I will say that this is definitely novel studies.

00:06:10.399 --> 00:06:14.559
Like, we're not doing a cliff-edge thing where we switch everything to R overnight,

00:06:15.679 --> 00:06:16.959
but it is a big change.

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:21.359
We expect that over the next few years, we'll have more and more studies using R as their

00:06:21.359 --> 00:06:26.799
core data science tool until we're using it as our primary tool across all of our studies.

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:33.519
And this, as I say, is the first step in this journey where in future, we can move flexibly

00:06:33.519 --> 00:06:34.239
in the future.

00:06:34.239 --> 00:06:36.239
So R isn't our destination.

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:41.519
It's part of a journey that allows us to move towards what the best data science tool is

00:06:41.519 --> 00:06:42.239
in the future.

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:47.359
So just a bit of context setting for this, if you're not super familiar with Pharma,

00:06:48.799 --> 00:06:54.559
Pharma, in general, has typically used commercial software to support filings.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:59.679
I think that's been true across the industry, and it's been true for a really long time.

00:06:59.679 --> 00:07:02.320
That's kind of the way we've been doing things.

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:05.519
And there's lots of historical reasons I won't get into there.

00:07:05.519 --> 00:07:10.239
But it does mean that our talent and tools, at least historically, were used for a lot

00:07:10.239 --> 00:07:11.279
of this.

00:07:11.279 --> 00:07:18.160
You know, we have a code base that's been built up over 20, 30 years, and a talent base

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:20.559
that's been using that code base for this time.

00:07:20.559 --> 00:07:24.720
So that's kind of just to highlight why this shift is big for us.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.079
So why are we doing this?

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:32.880
There's loads of different reasons that have inspired us to make this change.

00:07:33.519 --> 00:07:37.440
I'm going to highlight a few today, but I wouldn't say that this is an exhaustive list.

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:43.519
When it comes to R in particular, R is something that had been used at Rush for a while, but

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:50.000
I would say the kind of wedge product that got it used a lot more at PD Data Sciences

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:51.920
in particular was R Shiny.

00:07:52.799 --> 00:07:57.920
R Shiny really offered capabilities we didn't have already in the tools we had.

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:03.839
The ability to make these interactive apps using code so quickly and simply really proved

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:10.640
a really attractive offer and really encouraged us to start using R at least behind the scenes

00:08:10.640 --> 00:08:12.160
in clinical studies.

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:17.600
And in fact, one of the earliest R packages that was built in-house to support this was

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:22.079
a package called Teal, which Thomas is going to talk about later.

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:23.200
This is now open source.

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:28.480
You can follow that URL to go to see that package right now.

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:31.679
And this was an in-house solution for standardized Shiny apps.

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:37.039
So we had this kind of justification for why we wanted to start using R more.

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:42.159
And then there were a few other things that really started to weigh us towards thinking

00:08:42.159 --> 00:08:47.039
about moving towards R. One was just about the talent base.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:52.479
Generally speaking, when we're recruiting new graduates, they're much more likely to

00:08:52.479 --> 00:08:57.919
know these open source tools such as R or indeed Python than they are commercial software.

00:08:58.719 --> 00:09:05.520
But the final point, which I think is a bit more future looking, is we wanted to go open

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:06.320
source.

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:11.840
And the reason for this is we think open source offers loads of opportunities for how we work.

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:16.640
The first is just around getting latest developments more rapidly.

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:22.960
Typically, if there's a new statistical method used to analyze data, that will often be implemented

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:24.479
in R, first of all.

00:09:24.479 --> 00:09:29.840
So if we want to get access to those more quickly to provide better results, then we

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:30.799
should be using R.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.280
The other is we knew we wanted to go language agnostic.

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:38.559
We knew we wanted that ability to switch between languages.

00:09:38.559 --> 00:09:41.760
And we know that open source is going to make that easier.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:46.640
Because with no proprietary formats, it's usually easier to switch between contexts.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:50.880
And the obvious example of this is the ability to switch between R and Python.

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:54.719
There's been a lot of effort to make those two languages talk to each other nicely.

00:09:55.599 --> 00:09:59.359
And the last one, which is one I'm really excited about, and Thomas is going to talk

00:09:59.359 --> 00:10:03.840
about a bit more in a minute, is the ability to collaborate with external partners.

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:09.440
So up until a few years ago, all of our code was created entirely in-house.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:13.359
It wasn't really possible for us to work with people from outside of Rush.

00:10:13.359 --> 00:10:18.320
But if we go open source, we suddenly have this ability to get the inputs of people from

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:23.599
across the industry, which I think is in the long run going to lead to much more efficient

00:10:23.599 --> 00:10:27.840
and better code and ultimately better outcomes for us and for our patients.

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:34.239
So hopefully that's been a good introduction as to why we're doing what we're doing.

00:10:34.239 --> 00:10:39.200
And now I'm going to pass over to Thomas, who's going to talk a bit about, as I say,

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:42.159
the environment and the tools we're using in that environment.

00:10:43.919 --> 00:10:44.960
Thank you so much, Kieran.

00:10:45.919 --> 00:10:50.479
So then let's talk about the building blocks of this kind of modern data science platform

00:10:50.479 --> 00:10:54.320
we set out to create, which is really focused on open source as its backbone.

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:01.760
So first of all, I would just like to quickly dive a bit more detail into the requirements

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:04.559
we and PD data scientists have for our day to day work.

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:10.080
And generally, we can separate our task into either the regulatory side of things or the

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:11.280
exploratory side of things.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:16.479
And on the regulatory side of things, there's really four main deliverables we need to create.

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:18.239
The first one is called STTM.

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:22.719
So STTM is an industry standard for the data we collect in clinical trials.

00:11:22.719 --> 00:11:26.799
So regardless of how the data is collected in the end, when you submit it to the health

00:11:26.799 --> 00:11:31.760
authority, it has to be in this data standard such that it's harmonized across companies.

00:11:32.559 --> 00:11:35.520
Next up, we have the analysis or atom data sets.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:41.039
And here you take the STTM data sets as source and then you transform them in a way that

00:11:41.039 --> 00:11:42.960
suits your analysis downstream.

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:47.119
So as a quick example, imagine you collect a questionnaire which has 10 questions and

00:11:47.119 --> 00:11:48.719
an overall summary score.

00:11:48.719 --> 00:11:52.400
So the 10 questions you would have in your STTM data, because that's the raw data as

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:53.119
collected.

00:11:53.119 --> 00:11:57.919
But then you would calculate the summary overall score as part of your atom transformation.

00:11:59.119 --> 00:12:04.000
Next up, we need to perform a bunch of statistical analyses, and that can be something as simple

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.159
and descriptive as counting adverse events or something much more complex, for example,

00:12:08.159 --> 00:12:11.760
fitting a survival model or fitting a mixed measures repeat model.

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:17.520
And finally, we need to put those statistical analysis into an easily digestible format.

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:20.239
And that's generally either tables, listings or graphs.

00:12:21.039 --> 00:12:25.359
And all these four components combined make up the packages that we submit to health authorities,

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:30.000
such as the US FDA, in order to get market approval for novel therapeutics we're working

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:30.400
on.

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:32.159
So this is really at the core of our business.

00:12:33.599 --> 00:12:36.239
But of course, we also have the exploratory side of things.

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:40.000
And here, really, it's highly context dependent what we need to perform.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.559
And therefore, we need flexible tools and really the best tool for the job.

00:12:44.559 --> 00:12:48.080
So having an open source background where you have access to multiple language, for

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:51.359
example, is really a good thing in this context.

00:12:52.239 --> 00:12:56.960
We also need to consider that there's novel data modalities we're getting more and more.

00:12:56.960 --> 00:13:01.440
For example, imaging data is becoming rapidly and more in our trials, digital biomarker,

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:02.880
omics data, et cetera.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:07.359
So it's not just the classical rectangular data anymore, which we used to analyze in

00:13:07.359 --> 00:13:08.400
our commercial software.

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:15.359
And finally, we want not only to enable our data scientists to easily explore our data,

00:13:15.359 --> 00:13:20.880
but also people who don't work in data science, our colleagues in safety or clinical scientists.

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:26.320
And we want to really enable them to easily explore their data and do so in a reproducible

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:29.919
manner such that they don't always have to come back to us as data science.

00:13:29.919 --> 00:13:31.440
And we have this long feedback loop.

00:13:32.159 --> 00:13:36.880
And really, all of this combined necessitated that we created a next generation statistical

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:40.719
computing platform where we could really perform all these analyses.

00:13:41.919 --> 00:13:46.640
And this is where Ocean comes into play, our one central analytics environment, which is

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:49.760
the home for both our exploratory and regulatory work.

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:56.799
So Ocean is built in the cloud on AWS, and it's a language agnostic platform, which right

00:13:56.799 --> 00:14:00.799
now supports our Python as well as SAS for our legacy work.

00:14:00.799 --> 00:14:04.159
But it is easily extendable because it's based on Docker containers.

00:14:04.159 --> 00:14:08.400
So if you spin up a container with, for example, Julia in it, suddenly you would have access

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:09.440
to that language as well.

00:14:10.799 --> 00:14:13.440
For version control, we are using Git and GitLab.

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:18.080
And we're not only using that for our packages we develop internally, but it actually will

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:20.559
be there to store the code for all our studies.

00:14:20.559 --> 00:14:24.960
So if on a study you program a particular atom data set or an adverse event table, the

00:14:24.960 --> 00:14:27.039
code for that will be stored on GitLab.

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:33.919
Next up, and this is really a big change, even though it sounds somewhat silly, but

00:14:33.919 --> 00:14:40.400
we moved away from this proprietary format, SAS 7 BDAD, that used to be the only format

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:42.640
really that we used to store our CDIS data.

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:46.960
And instead, we opted for an open source format called Parquet, which is developed by the

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:48.239
Apache Foundation.

00:14:48.239 --> 00:14:53.200
And it's a binary format for handling rectangular data, and it's highly efficient in both reading

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:56.159
and writing, and it has served us already very well so far.

00:14:57.359 --> 00:15:01.520
We have an internal RStudio Connect server as part of this platform where we house our

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:05.679
exploratory Shiny apps, and we have a validated R package repository.

00:15:06.239 --> 00:15:11.599
So while typically you would install packages from CRAN, internally, we use this validated

00:15:11.599 --> 00:15:15.840
package repository, and you would find a lot of packages that you know from CRAN, such

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:21.280
as ggplot2 or dplyr over there as well, as well as our own open source packages we develop,

00:15:21.280 --> 00:15:22.960
plus internal packages.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:28.559
And it goes through our own internal, really streamlined and efficient validation process,

00:15:28.559 --> 00:15:29.760
which is called autovalidate.

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:35.359
Then we are using another open source tool called SnakeMake to orchestrate our production

00:15:35.359 --> 00:15:35.840
runs.

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:42.000
And SnakeMake is very clever in a way because it creates a directed acyclical graph of all

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:43.840
the artifacts that you need to create.

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:46.719
So think of your SCTMs, your atoms, your TLGs.

00:15:46.719 --> 00:15:51.440
And then it really paralyzes as much as possible, taking dependencies into account.

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:56.799
So what used to take maybe a whole day, for example, to run everything for a final clinical

00:15:56.799 --> 00:16:00.000
study report now is done in a matter of hours, if not minutes.

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:06.719
And finally, Ocean is the tool, is the home of our next-gen tools for clinical reporting,

00:16:06.719 --> 00:16:10.559
and I will spend the rest of my part talking about these next-gen tools.

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:18.320
So the first one of those is called OAK, and OAK is our solution for automating SCTM

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:18.960
mapping.

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:24.640
So SCTM mapping used to take a considerable amount of our time, and it was a rather labor

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:27.520
intensive process that was also somewhat mundane.

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:31.840
So we really opted to streamline this by creating an automation solution.

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:37.119
And driven by metadata and our global data standards at Roche, OAK can now automate around

00:16:37.119 --> 00:16:42.400
80% of SCTM domains with around 22 reasonable mapping algorithms.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.679
And this, in turn, then really saved us a lot of time.

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:49.840
We've seen already efficiency gains by at least 50%, so this is really huge.

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:54.320
And finally, it's actually a fairly simple tool to use because it's, at the end of the

00:16:54.320 --> 00:16:57.840
day, a single R package you interact with plus a web app.

00:16:57.840 --> 00:17:03.440
But that being said, under the hood, it's somewhat more complex because it has to interact

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:06.800
with several systems, and that's actually why it's called the OAK Garden.

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:10.959
And the first component of this garden is called Pistol and Honeybee.

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:15.599
So really, what you have to think about is we have a metadata repository at Roche, which

00:17:15.599 --> 00:17:16.880
is a graph database.

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:22.319
And inside that, we store the mappings from the raw data as we collect it to this SCTM

00:17:22.319 --> 00:17:24.400
standard in a machine-readable format.

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:28.560
And that's really key here because that makes it then easy for R, for example, to query

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:30.079
this information and make use of it.

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:35.680
Next up, we have our SCTM spec creator, which is called Mint.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:41.920
So this is a web application in React to create the study-specific SCTM mappings.

00:17:41.920 --> 00:17:47.920
And when I say that, really, most of it, at least 80% from what I had on a previous slide,

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:50.880
should already be automated there if you adhere to standards.

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:56.640
And then in this app, you have additional functionality to add any non-standard mappings.

00:17:56.640 --> 00:18:02.160
If, for example, you collect somewhat new data endpoints, which are not yet in our standards.

00:18:02.719 --> 00:18:06.319
All of this is then saved in a repository, which is called SEPHRON.

00:18:07.199 --> 00:18:12.239
And again, in a machine-readable format, namely JSON, such that it may query down the road

00:18:12.239 --> 00:18:17.599
in R. And very importantly, any non-standards you would define in the Mint application,

00:18:17.599 --> 00:18:22.479
you would save in SEPHRON, such that you can reuse these non-standard mappings

00:18:22.479 --> 00:18:23.920
across different studies.

00:18:25.280 --> 00:18:28.880
And finally, we have the actual data transformation engine, which is called OAP.

00:18:28.880 --> 00:18:30.160
And it's the R package.

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:32.719
It's the R package people in the end would use.

00:18:32.719 --> 00:18:34.479
And really, it's a very streamlined process.

00:18:34.479 --> 00:18:37.280
You fetch all this metadata from SEPHRON, basically.

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:40.239
And then you have a single function call per SCTM domain.

00:18:40.239 --> 00:18:44.239
And given all this metadata, it will then output for SCTM datasets.

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:48.800
So the Oak Garden is not open source.

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:53.839
And the reason for that being is that it's fairly tailored towards our internal Roche

00:18:53.839 --> 00:18:54.640
architecture.

00:18:54.640 --> 00:18:58.479
But that being said, the overall principle is really broadly applicable to anyone who

00:18:58.479 --> 00:19:03.280
has to map SCTM datasets, which is also the reason why we're in active talks with the

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:08.239
CDISC Open Source Alliance to create a proof of concept in which we would use CDASH rather

00:19:08.239 --> 00:19:12.000
than our own internal data collection standard as a source.

00:19:12.719 --> 00:19:17.680
And if that's something you and your organization are interested in to collaborate,

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:20.239
potentially, then please reach out.

00:19:20.239 --> 00:19:24.640
I certainly have heard a lot of questions regarding SCTM and R at RnPharma.

00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:27.199
So this might be a good opportunity to reach out.

00:19:27.199 --> 00:19:30.160
And maybe a good collaboration can spring out of that.

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:35.680
So we cover the first pillar of our regulatory reporting site.

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:38.319
And now it's time for the second, which is the Atom datasets.

00:19:38.319 --> 00:19:42.880
And here, our solution is called Atom, which is an open source modular toolkit for Atom

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:44.079
dataset creation in R.

00:19:44.719 --> 00:19:49.280
And what is really unique about Atom is that unlike other packages we developed, which

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:54.239
are now open source, this did not start out as a closed source internal project.

00:19:54.239 --> 00:19:56.239
And then later on got open source.

00:19:56.239 --> 00:20:01.839
Really, from the start of it, we collaborated with another organization, namely GSK, to

00:20:01.839 --> 00:20:06.000
hit the ground running and build something that would be usable not only for Rush's

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:07.920
purposes, but really for the industry as a whole.

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:10.880
And I think it's fair to say that this has been quite a success.

00:20:10.880 --> 00:20:14.079
We certainly want to use this kind of model of collaboration going forward.

00:20:14.959 --> 00:20:19.359
And when I say success, I think one metric that really hits that home is that what started

00:20:19.359 --> 00:20:23.839
out as this collaboration between two organizations to create one R package, now is

00:20:23.839 --> 00:20:27.839
actually an ecosystem of R packages, which are developed by seven pharmaceutical

00:20:27.839 --> 00:20:28.959
organizations in total.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:34.079
So in addition to Atom, we now have Atom Onco, where Amgen and Bristol Myers Whip

00:20:34.079 --> 00:20:35.839
joined us with their oncology expertise.

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:42.160
There is the Atom Opta package, which Nobartis and Rush are working on together.

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:46.800
And finally, GSK is collaborating with Pfizer and Johnson & Johnson on this Atom vaccines

00:20:46.800 --> 00:20:47.199
package.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:54.800
And if you and your organization are interested in leveraging R and Atom and Admiral for Atom

00:20:54.800 --> 00:20:59.599
dataset transformation and you have expertise in a particular therapeutic area, again, please

00:20:59.599 --> 00:21:00.160
reach out.

00:21:00.719 --> 00:21:02.880
We would really love to see this ecosystem growing.

00:21:05.439 --> 00:21:09.040
Next up, I want to talk about our statistical engineering team, which is really working

00:21:09.040 --> 00:21:13.680
at this intersection of biostatistics and statistical or software engineering, actually.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:18.079
So this team really focuses on accelerating the adoption of novel statistical methods.

00:21:18.079 --> 00:21:22.400
So really all the cutting edge stuff that comes out of academia and trying to implement

00:21:22.400 --> 00:21:23.199
that as software.

00:21:24.239 --> 00:21:29.599
And so far, this has been mainly focused on R packages and also occasionally standard

00:21:29.599 --> 00:21:31.680
or C++ have been used in the background.

00:21:31.680 --> 00:21:35.280
But the team is really open also to other languages, for example, Julia, basically

00:21:35.280 --> 00:21:38.959
anything that is open source and a viable solution for statistical computing.

00:21:39.280 --> 00:21:44.239
And really important to highlight is this this team is not only working at Roche alone,

00:21:44.239 --> 00:21:48.479
but it's part of a larger industry wide effort, namely the software engineering working

00:21:48.479 --> 00:21:52.880
group of the American Statistical Association, where not only Roche and other pharmaceutical

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:57.920
companies, but also academic institutions jointly work together to basically implement

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:01.040
the cutting edge of statistics in software.

00:22:01.040 --> 00:22:05.359
And here's just a couple of examples of packages the statistical engineering team has worked

00:22:05.359 --> 00:22:05.920
on.

00:22:05.920 --> 00:22:10.640
The MRMM package down there is actually the first one that came out of the software engineering

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:11.680
working group.

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:15.280
And another one I would like to highlight is this RBMI package for reference based model

00:22:15.280 --> 00:22:19.760
imputation, which won an award by the Roche Statistical Society last year.

00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:23.359
Once again, this has been a collaborative effort in this case between Roche and the

00:22:23.359 --> 00:22:25.680
University of Bath, so an academic institution.

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:33.439
So finally, on the regulatory side of things, we have the creation of a new regulatory

00:22:34.079 --> 00:22:34.640
side of things.

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:37.520
We have the creation of our tables, listings and graphs.

00:22:37.520 --> 00:22:42.079
And really, when we started doing that in R, the G part, the graph part was the easy

00:22:42.079 --> 00:22:42.479
one.

00:22:42.479 --> 00:22:44.479
We just used gtplot2.

00:22:44.479 --> 00:22:46.479
It was the best tool available for the job.

00:22:46.479 --> 00:22:47.839
It still is, in our opinion.

00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:52.719
And it was certainly also a big reason why to shift to R in the first place, having such

00:22:52.719 --> 00:22:54.319
a good tool readily available.

00:22:54.319 --> 00:22:58.640
However, the T side of things, the tables, especially if you look a couple of years back,

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:01.839
there was not such a really good solution out there.

00:23:01.839 --> 00:23:04.959
So what we did is we created our own, which is called RTables.

00:23:06.319 --> 00:23:10.800
And RTables really has an expressive and modern API for table generation in R.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:14.640
And very importantly, it is built from the ground up with the needs of clinical reporting

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:15.359
in mind.

00:23:15.359 --> 00:23:19.520
And we think that this is really key because the kinds of tables you do in this space tend

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:24.959
to be much more hierarchical and complex than, say, a typical table you would find in an

00:23:24.959 --> 00:23:26.959
academic journal or even on some websites.

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:33.839
Right now, RTables supports outputting tables in plain text, Word, PowerPoint, PDF, HTML,

00:23:33.839 --> 00:23:38.239
and the version on GitHub, the development version right now, also added RTF support.

00:23:39.680 --> 00:23:43.439
And this is an open source package which you can install from either GitHub or CRAN.

00:23:45.599 --> 00:23:49.040
Something that is working in tandem with RTables is TURN.

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:53.520
And it's really a complement that focuses around the summary statistics because you

00:23:53.599 --> 00:23:58.560
can think of it as bridging the statistical analysis you perform, for example, with one

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:02.959
of the packages we've seen on the previous slide, and then actually getting them to display

00:24:02.959 --> 00:24:03.599
in the table.

00:24:04.160 --> 00:24:08.400
And this is yet again an open source package which is readily available for you also to

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:09.199
use and check out.

00:24:11.040 --> 00:24:14.079
The final piece on that kind of TLG side of things is Chevron.

00:24:14.079 --> 00:24:17.839
And this is really about streamlining our processes even further.

00:24:17.839 --> 00:24:22.319
So when we started out doing tables in R, we had an internal TLG catalog, which looked

00:24:22.319 --> 00:24:23.199
something like this.

00:24:23.439 --> 00:24:25.359
This is a particular first event table.

00:24:25.359 --> 00:24:30.000
And you can see it's just kind of a code dump you would copy-paste into your study folder

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:30.880
and then use.

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:32.959
But really, copy-pasting is not a good solution.

00:24:32.959 --> 00:24:36.079
So we opted for something sort of template-based.

00:24:36.079 --> 00:24:40.239
And right now, you can basically create the same table by using the Chevron run function,

00:24:40.239 --> 00:24:43.599
indicating the template you want to use, and then feeding in your data.

00:24:43.599 --> 00:24:44.479
And off you go.

00:24:44.479 --> 00:24:47.280
So a further gain in efficiency in that way.

00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:52.479
So finally, let's talk also about the exploratory side of things.

00:24:53.199 --> 00:24:56.719
So I mentioned in the beginning, we want to enable our non-data scientist colleagues

00:24:56.719 --> 00:25:02.079
to also easily and, importantly, reproducibly analyze their clinical trial data.

00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:08.479
So we set out on this journey and said that R Shiny would be really a good solution for

00:25:08.479 --> 00:25:08.719
that.

00:25:08.719 --> 00:25:13.040
However, we just have a problem, which is, how do we actually get our 600 or so data

00:25:13.040 --> 00:25:17.280
scientists who are not Shiny developers to build these exploratory apps in the first

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:17.520
place?

00:25:18.160 --> 00:25:23.760
We did not want to train all of these 600 people to become sort of Shiny gurus.

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:28.400
Instead, what we opted for is to create this framework called Teal, which Kiran already

00:25:28.400 --> 00:25:29.599
mentioned in the beginning.

00:25:29.599 --> 00:25:32.719
And this framework really centers around reusable modules.

00:25:32.719 --> 00:25:36.640
And it really abstracts away a lot of the complexities of building Shiny apps from

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:37.199
scratch.

00:25:37.199 --> 00:25:41.520
You don't actually have to care so much about the UI as well as the server logic in the

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:44.239
modules you would readily adopt from the catalog.

00:25:44.719 --> 00:25:48.239
This is an example of a very simple app created using Teal.

00:25:48.239 --> 00:25:52.880
And you can see on the top, you have all these tabs and each of those tabs represents a

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:54.079
particular module.

00:25:54.079 --> 00:25:56.479
So in this case, it's a demographic table module.

00:25:56.479 --> 00:25:59.920
And what all nodes have in common is that in the center, you have a display.

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:02.079
In this case, it's a table, but it could also be a plot.

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:06.640
And then on the left, in addition, you have this encoding panel where you can kind of

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:08.959
customize what you see in this table.

00:26:08.959 --> 00:26:12.400
For example, here, you could select different variables to be displayed.

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:14.640
So that's all the module specific part.

00:26:15.199 --> 00:26:20.400
And as I said, we have a large catalog, I think even over 100 modules readily available

00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:24.560
for our internal people and also for you, because this is open source to use.

00:26:25.359 --> 00:26:29.839
But then the Teal framework itself also provides a couple of goodies that work across

00:26:29.839 --> 00:26:34.000
all modules, the first one of which is this filter panel you see here on the right.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:38.319
So depending on which data is used in a particular module, it would list out the data set

00:26:38.319 --> 00:26:39.040
on top.

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:42.719
And then you have the ability to select any variable out of these data sets to drill down

00:26:42.719 --> 00:26:43.359
the data.

00:26:43.359 --> 00:26:46.959
So in this case, we have a particular subgroup based on ADSL.

00:26:46.959 --> 00:26:50.400
But if you imagine this would be some kind of adverse event analysis, you could easily

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:53.359
filter down for, let's say, serious adverse events.

00:26:54.959 --> 00:26:58.560
Next up, we have this reporter functionality, and this is a really neat one.

00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:03.439
Anything that you create in any of these modules, you can add to a shopping basket, sort of.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:12.160
And then at the end of the day, you can go to the card and check out by exporting a PDF

00:27:12.160 --> 00:27:16.800
report or a PowerPoint report, which would then contain everything that you added to

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:17.520
the card.

00:27:17.520 --> 00:27:21.439
So maybe a demographic table, a couple of my upload, a response table, whatever you

00:27:21.439 --> 00:27:21.920
may wish.

00:27:23.119 --> 00:27:26.000
And finally, we have this show R code button functionality.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:31.359
And this is really key for us because that enables the reproducible nature of Teal, because

00:27:31.359 --> 00:27:36.319
unlike Tableau, for example, or Spotify, which are also great tools to visualize data

00:27:36.319 --> 00:27:37.040
and drill down.

00:27:38.239 --> 00:27:42.560
This is really 100% reproducible because if you click the button, you will get a complete

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:47.280
R script, including loading all packages, loading all data that is needed, filtering

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:52.319
the data as you have in the filter panel here, and then reproducing the exact display that

00:27:52.319 --> 00:27:52.959
you see here.

00:27:53.839 --> 00:27:56.560
And that's really, we think, a key for us.

00:27:57.439 --> 00:28:02.800
So I already mentioned this has been open source since last year, and the code is available

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:05.359
on GitHub for you to look at and also to install it from there.

00:28:06.079 --> 00:28:10.800
We have two sample apps which are publicly available, and the previous picture I showed

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:11.760
is one of those.

00:28:11.760 --> 00:28:13.119
So definitely check those out.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:18.560
And actually, Teal has been used in an R submission pilot to the FDA, which is quite an

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:22.880
exciting development, kind of instead of the static TLG submitting a shiny app.

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:25.359
And there will be more communication about that in the future.

00:28:27.040 --> 00:28:30.959
We have an upcoming webinar around Teal at the end of February, where we will dive deep

00:28:30.959 --> 00:28:33.920
into this particular tool for an hour or so.

00:28:34.640 --> 00:28:38.400
And finally, we are looking for collaborators to develop this framework further.

00:28:38.400 --> 00:28:42.160
And I think that really goes to all the tools that we've shown here, kind of in the spirit

00:28:42.160 --> 00:28:46.000
of the open source community, where we take a lot of the great stuff that other peoples

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:47.119
have put out there.

00:28:47.119 --> 00:28:52.959
We also want to put the packages we develop out there and collaborate with others to develop

00:28:52.959 --> 00:28:53.520
them further.

00:28:53.839 --> 00:28:58.880
And finally, I would just like to mention that this everything sort of I said is part

00:28:58.880 --> 00:29:03.040
of this larger effort in the industry called the Pharmaverse, where different pharmaceutical

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:07.439
companies come together and develop R packages for end-to-end clinical reporting.

00:29:07.439 --> 00:29:14.400
That's really a great development, which we really hope further gains traction this year

00:29:14.400 --> 00:29:15.599
and the years to come.

00:29:15.599 --> 00:29:17.599
And with that being said, Kieran, I hand it back to you.

00:29:23.520 --> 00:29:25.599
Oh, thanks, Thomas.

00:29:28.319 --> 00:29:36.160
So yeah, Thomas has spent some time talking about the sort of setup of how we're going

00:29:36.160 --> 00:29:37.520
to do our rush.

00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:41.760
So we've kind of it's not all finished, but it's very close to finish.

00:29:41.760 --> 00:29:44.719
You know, it's a work in progress where we have this environment we're going to work

00:29:44.719 --> 00:29:46.239
and we have this tool base.

00:29:46.239 --> 00:29:49.839
And certainly both of those are going to continuously evolve over time.

00:29:49.839 --> 00:29:52.880
But we have a good idea of what we're doing there.

00:29:52.880 --> 00:29:54.079
And we've presented that now.

00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:58.959
But the other piece that we really can't forget about when it comes to moving to a

00:29:58.959 --> 00:30:04.000
new language is looking at our talent base, making sure that they're ready for this change.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.239
And it definitely is a big change.

00:30:06.239 --> 00:30:08.400
You know, it's not just about shifting to R.

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:10.400
We're changing the environment we're working in.

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:11.359
We're changing the tools.

00:30:11.359 --> 00:30:13.040
We're using version control.

00:30:13.040 --> 00:30:15.439
So there's a lot of things for our talent to learn.

00:30:15.439 --> 00:30:17.520
And we need to make sure that they're supported.

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:22.000
So what I'm going to talk about for the next 10 minutes or so is just about some of the

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.640
measures we're taking to support everyone.

00:30:25.199 --> 00:30:27.680
And this is all, you know, this is a work in progress.

00:30:27.680 --> 00:30:30.479
This is something we're learning with as we're going.

00:30:30.479 --> 00:30:35.280
And certainly I expect to be giving future talks in a year's time where we talk about

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:36.800
what worked and what doesn't.

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:40.640
But here's at least some of our ideas that we're kind of throwing out there right now.

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:46.400
So just thinking for a second about who we have working in PD Data Sciences.

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:50.319
There's a real mix of different people here.

00:30:50.319 --> 00:30:55.520
We have people who've been in the industry for 20 or 30 years and have never coded an

00:30:55.520 --> 00:30:56.079
R at all.

00:30:56.079 --> 00:31:00.239
So they have a wealth of experience in clinical trials, but they don't have much experience

00:31:00.239 --> 00:31:03.119
in R in particular or Git as well.

00:31:03.119 --> 00:31:07.040
And then we have people who are our experts.

00:31:07.199 --> 00:31:13.920
We've got a lot of people who've joined the company more recently who, as I kind of alluded

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:19.359
to earlier, have this R experience and haven't had the opportunity to apply it in the context

00:31:19.359 --> 00:31:20.400
of clinical reporting.

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:25.920
The other challenge we have is that not everyone's transitioning to R at the same time.

00:31:25.920 --> 00:31:30.319
So again, this is something I mentioned in the intro that we're not, you know, we're

00:31:30.319 --> 00:31:34.880
not moving every single person to R all at once.

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:36.880
We're doing it in a phased way.

00:31:36.959 --> 00:31:40.800
And that's good from a management point of view, but it does mean that you can't just

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:45.119
give everyone training one day and expect them to be able to apply it the next day.

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:50.719
And the other thing that I think is really important when you think about transitioning

00:31:50.719 --> 00:31:55.439
to a new language, it's not about just learning kind of how to use that language.

00:31:55.439 --> 00:31:57.680
It's also about being fluent in that language.

00:31:58.239 --> 00:32:02.880
We really want our programmers to start being able to know what good R code looks like,

00:32:02.880 --> 00:32:06.079
not just be able to throw something together that just about works.

00:32:07.760 --> 00:32:14.640
So as I say, I'm going to go through some of the solutions we've looked at for dealing

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:15.439
with these issues.

00:32:17.199 --> 00:32:22.400
So the big one, I think, is around helping guide our users.

00:32:23.280 --> 00:32:29.040
So because of all those challenges we have, doing active live training isn't always going

00:32:29.040 --> 00:32:30.239
to be possible.

00:32:30.239 --> 00:32:34.959
Realistically, in terms of resource restraints and the fact that everyone's not transitioning

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:37.920
at once, it doesn't make sense to do live training.

00:32:37.920 --> 00:32:42.800
It's certainly something we'll do, but we need people to be able to do self-study.

00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:46.880
And the problem with self-study is that if you just put someone in a room and tell them

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:50.719
to learn a subject, they might be able to do it, but it's going to be challenging.

00:32:50.719 --> 00:32:53.520
They're not going to know where to start necessarily.

00:32:53.520 --> 00:32:59.280
And in particular, they might go on a journey that helps them a bit, but isn't as guided

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:00.000
as it should be.

00:33:00.719 --> 00:33:04.560
So we've been looking at a few different ways to make this more effective.

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:11.280
The first idea is to work out what people don't know.

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:17.439
Often when we've been sending out initial surveys on people's knowledge on subjects,

00:33:17.439 --> 00:33:19.040
we do it in a kind of granular way.

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:22.000
We say, you know, how long have you been programming this language?

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:23.839
How good do you think you are on it?

00:33:23.839 --> 00:33:28.560
And self-assessment on that level can be helpful, but it's often true, particularly when you're

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:32.000
starting a subject, that you kind of, you don't know what you don't know.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:36.479
So there may be gaps in your knowledge and you're just not aware of them because you're

00:33:36.479 --> 00:33:38.719
not familiar enough with the language.

00:33:38.719 --> 00:33:42.959
And certainly for those of you who are familiar with R, there's lots of pitfalls when it comes

00:33:42.959 --> 00:33:48.000
to the complexity of how R works, that if you're only starting off with R, you're not

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:49.920
going to necessarily know about.

00:33:49.920 --> 00:33:52.160
So that's what the data science profile does.

00:33:52.160 --> 00:33:58.800
It breaks all of these categories into discrete topics and then builds assertions on kind

00:33:58.800 --> 00:34:03.199
of knowledge we expect people to know to be considered proficient in that topic.

00:34:03.199 --> 00:34:06.640
So I've got a screenshot, which is an example here for Git.

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:11.600
And it's got a collection of different things I might expect as basic knowledge when you're

00:34:11.600 --> 00:34:12.959
starting in Git.

00:34:12.959 --> 00:34:15.760
And basically, this is all based on self-assessment.

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:17.919
So we're not trying to catch people out here.

00:34:17.919 --> 00:34:19.439
We're not trying to trap anyone.

00:34:19.439 --> 00:34:23.199
We want an honest reflection of where they are.

00:34:23.199 --> 00:34:27.280
And that helps them to understand where they need to focus their learning on.

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:37.840
So the next step is giving them the resources to fill those gaps that they have.

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:43.120
One important thing we've kind of thought about is we don't really want to reinvent

00:34:43.120 --> 00:34:43.840
the wheel.

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:48.320
What I mean by that is there can be a temptation when you've got some time and the ability

00:34:48.320 --> 00:34:53.199
to create training materials to go ahead and just start making training resources without

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:56.320
thinking maybe this resource exists already.

00:34:56.719 --> 00:35:01.600
There's a huge amount of material online, both free and available via commercial license.

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:03.199
And some of it is great.

00:35:04.239 --> 00:35:10.159
The challenge that a new learner has is they don't necessarily know how to direct themselves

00:35:10.159 --> 00:35:10.719
in this.

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:14.879
So we've already got a bit of a start, and they know the kind of topics they want to

00:35:14.879 --> 00:35:15.600
work on.

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:18.879
But even then, what are the best resources for them to use?

00:35:18.879 --> 00:35:21.600
And what orders should they be progressing through them in?

00:35:22.159 --> 00:35:26.639
So what we've built for this is an in-house solution, which we're calling the Data Science

00:35:26.639 --> 00:35:27.679
University.

00:35:27.679 --> 00:35:32.560
And what this is, is it's a tool to curate existing materials.

00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:37.280
So what we do, and we've got an example here, is we build learning paths on a particular

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:38.080
topic.

00:35:38.080 --> 00:35:44.000
So this is a good coding in R topic, where we pick out, we pick that into discrete topics.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:47.919
So again, that links to that data science profile of seeing where your gaps are.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:52.719
And in each one, we provide material that we think is of high quality for learning about

00:35:52.719 --> 00:35:53.760
that subject.

00:35:53.760 --> 00:35:57.840
And again, that may be an in-house training that we've created, but it could well be a

00:35:57.840 --> 00:36:00.239
great resource that's available for free online.

00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:08.639
So the other thing I wanted to mention as well is, obviously, a couple of these things

00:36:08.639 --> 00:36:14.000
are in-house, and you may be curious about some of the material we're producing at Rush.

00:36:14.159 --> 00:36:18.959
Well, I wanted to take a little opportunity to do a sneaky advert for something that's

00:36:18.959 --> 00:36:21.199
coming out very soon on Coursera.

00:36:21.199 --> 00:36:26.560
We've actually been building a Genentech-based course called Making Data Science Work for

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:27.600
Clinical Reporting.

00:36:28.479 --> 00:36:32.719
This is actually going to be part of a wider specialization, and it's going to look at

00:36:32.719 --> 00:36:36.719
how we think data science should be done in the context of clinical reporting.

00:36:37.600 --> 00:36:41.760
So this course is literally being beta tested this week.

00:36:41.760 --> 00:36:46.320
So I'm really hopeful that it's going to be out either this month or early in February.

00:36:46.320 --> 00:36:50.959
So look out for that if you're interested in the kind of material we're producing around

00:36:51.679 --> 00:36:54.959
learning how to use data science in the context of clinical reporting.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:04.879
So when it comes to making training resources, one thing that I think is really key that's

00:37:04.879 --> 00:37:08.879
kind of been learned by hard experience is try to make sure it's relevant.

00:37:09.040 --> 00:37:14.159
One experience we've had when we've, for instance, paid for external trainers to come

00:37:14.159 --> 00:37:20.560
here is that training material might be really great, but it doesn't take advantage of the

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:23.600
fact that we kind of know what we do for a living, right?

00:37:23.600 --> 00:37:27.679
We know what our programmers are doing in their day-to-day work.

00:37:27.679 --> 00:37:31.760
So when we develop trainings, we can make it relevant to what they're actually doing.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:37.840
It definitely involves an effort, but I think you get a lot of value by making problems real.

00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:43.520
One simple way of doing that is just picking out real data, not using empty colors or iris,

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:45.520
which is what you'll find on online resources.

00:37:46.239 --> 00:37:48.719
And that's what we've done in the trainings we've built in-house.

00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:55.280
There's actually an open source package that we've created specifically for generating

00:37:55.919 --> 00:38:01.919
synthetic CDISC data, so you can make use of that right now, and that's the link on the screen there.

00:38:04.719 --> 00:38:08.959
So the last point on training is making sure it's at the point of need.

00:38:08.959 --> 00:38:13.760
So this is kind of relating to what I was saying earlier on, that not everyone is moving

00:38:13.760 --> 00:38:17.040
towards using R all at once.

00:38:17.040 --> 00:38:21.360
So we're doing our best to focus our training on those who need it.

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:26.159
We're training in cohorts rather than trying to train everyone at once, because if you

00:38:26.159 --> 00:38:30.399
take a training a year before you actually apply it, you've basically wasted your time

00:38:30.399 --> 00:38:34.320
because you've forgotten everything you're using in that time period.

00:38:34.320 --> 00:38:36.560
So our goal is training at the point of need.

00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:43.199
So the last point I want to make, which is going to lead into Ning talking about the

00:38:43.199 --> 00:38:47.919
business transition, is that while I've talked a lot about training here, learning about

00:38:48.239 --> 00:38:52.800
is that while I've talked a lot about training here, learning really isn't about training.

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:55.199
So that relates to that last point.

00:38:55.199 --> 00:39:01.520
Realistically, how you learn is by applying all of those trainings in your actual day-to-day work.

00:39:02.159 --> 00:39:06.000
So we want to encourage that kind of context learning.

00:39:07.600 --> 00:39:12.399
And as well as that, we also want to build this culture where you are always looking

00:39:12.399 --> 00:39:13.919
to improve how you code.

00:39:13.919 --> 00:39:17.600
So this is speaking back to this idea of not just making people learn a language,

00:39:17.600 --> 00:39:19.840
but also becoming fluent in that.

00:39:19.840 --> 00:39:23.439
And there's a few different things we're focusing on to try and support that.

00:39:24.399 --> 00:39:27.520
One is about building good frameworks to apply knowledge.

00:39:27.520 --> 00:39:31.439
So in this environment we're building up, making sure we have good frameworks where

00:39:31.439 --> 00:39:35.520
we encourage people to follow best practice just by those frameworks.

00:39:36.719 --> 00:39:41.679
The other is around learning via code review and seeing other people's code.

00:39:41.679 --> 00:39:46.399
Certainly, one of the ways I became a much better R programmer was by reading code written

00:39:46.399 --> 00:39:49.199
by someone who was a better programmer than me.

00:39:49.199 --> 00:39:55.040
And I had code that worked, but when I reviewed their code, I realized that I could be doing

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:59.600
things much more efficiently and writing code that's much clearer to read and easier to

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:00.879
use in the future.

00:40:00.879 --> 00:40:05.199
So we're really going to encourage this culture of code review, of looking at code and seeing

00:40:06.080 --> 00:40:07.280
how we can do better.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:13.600
And one connected idea with that, which was actually inspired by the tidyverse days run

00:40:13.600 --> 00:40:20.320
by Posit, was having these internal hack events, which we called HackR, where we basically

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:26.320
took all of those tools we're building that Thomas went through and highlighted issues

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:28.399
that we thought people could take on.

00:40:28.399 --> 00:40:32.000
So we said to our wider data science audience, get involved.

00:40:32.800 --> 00:40:34.879
You can improve these tools.

00:40:34.959 --> 00:40:39.439
And this is another way of highlighting this idea of an open source culture, the idea that

00:40:39.439 --> 00:40:45.919
these tools that we're using and developing to do our work, they're not made by wizards

00:40:45.919 --> 00:40:46.560
in the sky.

00:40:46.560 --> 00:40:51.679
They're something we can work on and improve, and we can collaborate together to lead to

00:40:51.679 --> 00:40:52.959
better code for all of us.

00:40:54.479 --> 00:40:59.360
So the last thing which is connected to that is learning as teams.

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:02.239
So I mentioned that we're not transitioning at once.

00:41:02.239 --> 00:41:07.120
So when we're bringing teams as a whole into this new environment, we're going to make

00:41:07.120 --> 00:41:12.560
sure that they learn together, because I think another way of learning quickly is by learning

00:41:12.560 --> 00:41:13.520
with peers.

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:16.000
So we're going to make sure that teams upskill together.

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:22.000
We're going to support people on their journey with additional mentoring, where we share

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:24.479
knowledge from individual to individual as well.

00:41:25.280 --> 00:41:31.360
So I'm going to pass now to Ning, who's going to talk a bit about how that transition for

00:41:31.360 --> 00:41:32.719
those teams is going to work.

00:41:36.719 --> 00:41:38.080
Thank you very much, Kieran.

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:42.879
Yeah, so I'll take over and talk about how we are making our business transition.

00:41:43.520 --> 00:41:49.280
Yeah, so as Thomas already alluded a little bit, like from Roche, we're a huge company.

00:41:49.280 --> 00:41:54.719
Within Roche Data Sciences, we have over 1,000 employees, and we are working on over 200

00:41:54.719 --> 00:41:56.080
active modules.

00:41:56.080 --> 00:42:00.639
So as you can imagine, we have a really diverse group over there with different skill set,

00:42:00.639 --> 00:42:04.000
different background, and also we have very diverse type of projects.

00:42:05.040 --> 00:42:11.520
And in addition to that, also, as you may already get a feeling from Thomas' presentation,

00:42:11.520 --> 00:42:17.280
that for this transition, the scale is very large, not only because we have a large team,

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:23.439
but also because there are so many new tools available out there, including the R packages,

00:42:23.439 --> 00:42:30.080
as well as some non-R tools, including Git, Docker, Cloud Computing, and SNAEMake.

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:35.520
This is the beauty of open source, but also you can imagine that that introduced additional

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:38.560
complication to our business transition.

00:42:40.479 --> 00:42:46.320
So to ensure a successful business transition, we realized that we really need to make sure

00:42:46.320 --> 00:42:52.000
that we can empower every single project team to make their own decision and also to make

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:54.479
their own fee-for-purpose transition plan.

00:42:54.479 --> 00:42:58.959
We're kind of thinking that for each project team, when they try to modernize their data

00:42:58.959 --> 00:43:02.639
science tools, it's sort of like renovating their house.

00:43:02.639 --> 00:43:07.439
So as we all know that when families decide to renovate their house, each family has their

00:43:07.439 --> 00:43:08.959
own needs.

00:43:08.959 --> 00:43:14.239
Some families may spend more time on renovating kitchen and bathroom, and maybe other families

00:43:14.239 --> 00:43:17.199
will spend more time on renovating living rooms.

00:43:17.199 --> 00:43:21.600
And for people who are purchasing a new house, they probably will pick out the new tools

00:43:21.600 --> 00:43:26.560
and new materials when remodeling their house.

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:31.280
Similarly, for analytical projects, we're thinking that during this transition journey,

00:43:31.280 --> 00:43:37.600
for some of the analytical project teams, maybe they think that it's valuable to refactor

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:41.679
everything, including data process, data analysis, etc.

00:43:41.679 --> 00:43:47.919
And maybe for other teams, their data processing pipeline is very stable using the existing

00:43:47.919 --> 00:43:53.199
tools, and they prefer to keep using the existing tools for data processing, but only adopt

00:43:53.199 --> 00:43:55.360
the new tools for data analysis.

00:43:55.360 --> 00:44:00.800
And for brand new projects, we think probably likely the project team would love to start

00:44:00.800 --> 00:44:02.479
from the newer tools.

00:44:02.479 --> 00:44:06.959
So we want to enable each project team to make a plan that are tailored to their need.

00:44:08.159 --> 00:44:14.719
In addition to that, similar to remodeling, each family probably have different best

00:44:14.719 --> 00:44:16.560
timing for their remodeling.

00:44:16.560 --> 00:44:21.280
So for analytical projects, we also think that different teams should have the flexibility

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:25.040
to pick up a good timing for their team to adopt this transition.

00:44:25.679 --> 00:44:30.320
Likely that that will be the time frame when they don't have too many business critical

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:31.120
deliverables.

00:44:31.679 --> 00:44:36.560
And lastly, of course, different analytical teams have different access to talent pool

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:37.520
and resources.

00:44:40.479 --> 00:44:47.280
Although we want to empower each individual team to make their own decision, as a big

00:44:47.280 --> 00:44:52.080
organization, you can imagine that like it's probably you will probably create a lot of

00:44:52.080 --> 00:44:57.840
chaos if we just go think push things in a decentralized way and ask everybody to make

00:44:57.840 --> 00:44:59.199
their own decisions.

00:44:59.199 --> 00:45:04.959
So as an organization, we still need to want to have some light coordinations across different

00:45:04.959 --> 00:45:05.360
teams.

00:45:06.080 --> 00:45:11.280
So at the end of the day, we really want to come up with the adoption role map for the

00:45:11.280 --> 00:45:12.560
next couple of months.

00:45:13.439 --> 00:45:20.800
With that, we will have a holistic understanding about how many teams are planning to be onboarded

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:25.199
in a certain time frame and what are their needs, what are the tools they need to learn,

00:45:25.199 --> 00:45:25.840
etc.

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:32.159
In addition to that, by having such an adoption role map, we also think this is a very good

00:45:32.159 --> 00:45:38.879
opportunity for us to build some mechanism to enable iterative feedback to our two developer

00:45:38.879 --> 00:45:39.439
team.

00:45:39.439 --> 00:45:44.959
We're hoping that for each wave of onboarding, there will be a mechanism to feedback to the

00:45:44.959 --> 00:45:50.239
two development team so that we can keep improving our tools as the onboarding goes.

00:45:52.800 --> 00:45:54.159
So how can we achieve that?

00:45:54.159 --> 00:45:56.800
How can we come up with such an adoption plan?

00:45:57.439 --> 00:46:01.919
So from Roche, we have a small group of people coming together, created this adoption

00:46:01.919 --> 00:46:08.080
scheduling team, and we work together with the project teams trying to work out this

00:46:08.080 --> 00:46:08.959
adoption plan.

00:46:09.600 --> 00:46:14.800
So the project teams will still be the final decision maker, but we have this scheduling

00:46:14.800 --> 00:46:20.719
team over there trying to coordinate the onboarding timing across different teams and also trying

00:46:20.719 --> 00:46:25.919
to provide consultations for them to understand the tool availability, etc.

00:46:26.639 --> 00:46:31.840
So what are some of the considerations when we build up our adoption role map?

00:46:32.800 --> 00:46:35.280
The first thing is definitely business continuity.

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:41.040
We want to make sure that for each project team, they can identify a couple of good transition

00:46:41.040 --> 00:46:48.159
timings for themselves and we can stick with those good timings so that we can minimize

00:46:48.159 --> 00:46:50.800
business interruption when doing this transition.

00:46:52.239 --> 00:46:57.600
Secondly, we also want to take this opportunity to enable early collaboration between the

00:46:57.600 --> 00:47:01.600
developers and also the users and to allow iterative development.

00:47:02.560 --> 00:47:08.080
Therefore, we decided to start our adoption at a very early stage, even before all the

00:47:08.080 --> 00:47:10.000
tools are 100% ready.

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:16.320
So we engaged a small number of users when the tools are still somewhat half-baked, and

00:47:16.320 --> 00:47:23.760
we ask for feedback and we also encourage the users to actually co-create with us by

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:28.560
filing bugs or by even contributing code back to the code base.

00:47:28.959 --> 00:47:37.520
The other thing we noticed from past experience is that if we look for early tester volunteers,

00:47:37.520 --> 00:47:42.479
sometimes we are getting those expert users being very active to be the early testers,

00:47:42.479 --> 00:47:46.800
but those users may not represent the majority of the user base.

00:47:46.800 --> 00:47:52.239
Therefore, when planning out this adoption role map, we reach out proactively to different

00:47:53.199 --> 00:48:00.399
teams and try to include a diverse type of project and user base in each wave to represent

00:48:00.399 --> 00:48:01.360
our user base.

00:48:03.280 --> 00:48:07.840
In addition to that, we also want to make sure that when we work out this role map,

00:48:08.959 --> 00:48:13.679
we want to ensure that the trainer and support capacity are considered.

00:48:13.679 --> 00:48:19.760
We don't want to overload our trainer or the support team in a short time frame, and we

00:48:19.760 --> 00:48:22.399
want to make sure all the users get sufficient support.

00:48:24.080 --> 00:48:31.120
And lastly, in the discussion between the scheduling team and also the project team,

00:48:31.919 --> 00:48:40.479
the scheduling team also provides consultations to help the project teams identify relevant

00:48:40.479 --> 00:48:42.879
tools and processes to be adopted.

00:48:42.879 --> 00:48:47.520
And as mentioned, not every single study needs to adopt all the tools out there.

00:48:48.080 --> 00:48:58.639
And also, as mentioned, for early adopters, not all the tools are ready when teams start

00:48:58.639 --> 00:49:04.560
to onboarding, so our scheduling team also makes sure that the project team's adoption

00:49:04.560 --> 00:49:07.199
timeline aligns with our tool availability.

00:49:10.639 --> 00:49:15.760
So to support this journey, as you can imagine, this is not something that can be driven by

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:17.040
a small group of people.

00:49:17.520 --> 00:49:25.120
Although it is Thomas and Kieran and myself presenting here today, there is really a large

00:49:25.120 --> 00:49:31.040
community behind who is driving this transition within Roche and also in the pharma industry.

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:34.959
And we really want to say thank you to everybody who got involved.

00:49:34.959 --> 00:49:40.639
And I also want to mention that for many people who are driving those activities, they are

00:49:40.639 --> 00:49:46.800
not spending 100% of their time on developing a software or spending 100% of their time

00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:48.639
on the change management part.

00:49:48.639 --> 00:49:54.239
Rather, the majority of people are still working on molecule teams, and they're spending 20%

00:49:54.239 --> 00:50:00.080
to 30% of their time on driving certain aspects of our transition here.

00:50:00.719 --> 00:50:05.199
So what are some of the communities that are driving this transition within Roche?

00:50:05.919 --> 00:50:08.479
The first one is definitely the software product teams.

00:50:08.479 --> 00:50:13.840
Those are the developers who wrote the R packages, who built the infrastructures, who wrote the

00:50:13.840 --> 00:50:14.639
business tools.

00:50:14.879 --> 00:50:19.520
We also have a ways of working community, and those are the people who are looking at

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:24.000
how we can integrate the new tools with existing business processes.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:31.360
And they also come up with new guidelines in terms of ways of working using newer tools.

00:50:32.800 --> 00:50:38.959
And there is this roadmap scheduling community, a group of people who interview with the project

00:50:39.919 --> 00:50:45.439
teams and provide consultation to the project teams to come up with an adoption roadmap.

00:50:46.479 --> 00:50:52.000
And when it comes to come closer to a project team's onboarding timeline, they will be

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:57.199
assigned with an onboarding coach, and the onboarding coach will help them to identify

00:50:57.199 --> 00:51:03.040
certain training materials that are relevant to their team, also point them to activities

00:51:03.040 --> 00:51:04.959
such as hackathons Kiran mentioned.

00:51:05.840 --> 00:51:10.560
And there is a user support community answering the questions from the users.

00:51:10.560 --> 00:51:19.919
And lastly, there is a communication community who share our adoption progress to the wider

00:51:19.919 --> 00:51:24.399
community and also share with people what to expect as the next step.

00:51:26.080 --> 00:51:27.600
So where are we right now?

00:51:27.600 --> 00:51:34.399
During Q3 to Q4 last year, we welcomed a couple of teams joining us as early adopters.

00:51:34.399 --> 00:51:38.159
We had two waves of early adopters join us.

00:51:38.159 --> 00:51:44.639
And as mentioned, for those early adopters, when they join us, our systems, our tools

00:51:44.639 --> 00:51:46.800
are not 100% ready yet.

00:51:46.800 --> 00:51:52.560
And they're really the trailblazers helping us to test out the tools and have early interventions,

00:51:52.560 --> 00:51:54.560
giving feedbacks, et cetera.

00:51:55.040 --> 00:52:01.040
And for those project teams, they did have some backup plans by using the existing tools

00:52:01.600 --> 00:52:05.120
because the newer tools and systems are not 100% ready yet.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:11.840
So in Q2 and Q3 this year, we will welcome a couple of new molecule teams joining us.

00:52:12.639 --> 00:52:18.399
So for those new molecule teams, they are the teams who don't have any legacy code.

00:52:18.399 --> 00:52:20.719
So they will start everything from scratch.

00:52:20.719 --> 00:52:27.120
So as you can imagine, they will be using the new tools end-to-end in an end-to-end

00:52:27.120 --> 00:52:34.959
fashion, and they will build this whole end-to-end process using our newer tools.

00:52:34.959 --> 00:52:39.280
And we're really excited to see how that testing goes.

00:52:39.280 --> 00:52:45.360
And after that, if everything goes smoothly, in Q4, we expect to welcome more studies,

00:52:45.439 --> 00:52:51.280
more project teams joining us for a wider rollout.

00:52:51.280 --> 00:52:57.199
In that rollout, we will welcome some of the new studies, and also we'll welcome some other

00:52:57.199 --> 00:53:02.399
projects who already have some existing code, and they will pick the part.

00:53:02.399 --> 00:53:07.600
They might decide to refactor some of their code, or maybe they just decide to migrate

00:53:07.600 --> 00:53:10.159
to the new system without refactoring their code.

00:53:11.120 --> 00:53:15.679
So the journey continues, and we're really, really excited to be part of this journey.

00:53:15.679 --> 00:53:21.439
And hopefully, if we got a chance to speak again in a year or so, we can share more good news.

00:53:22.479 --> 00:53:27.199
So with that, I think we are happy to take any questions.

00:53:31.280 --> 00:53:32.320
All right.

00:53:32.320 --> 00:53:32.879
Awesome.

00:53:33.439 --> 00:53:36.479
Thank you so much, Rosh and Genentech team.

00:53:36.479 --> 00:53:38.080
Lots of wonderful information.

00:53:38.080 --> 00:53:40.159
Tons of questions are coming in.

00:53:40.159 --> 00:53:44.800
I know we've got about six or seven minutes here, so I'm just going to jump right in with

00:53:44.800 --> 00:53:47.040
a couple of questions that are floating to the top.

00:53:47.679 --> 00:53:52.560
So the first one I'm seeing is, what hurdles did you have to overcome for transitioning

00:53:52.560 --> 00:53:56.399
from SAS 7 BDAT to Parquet files for data storage?

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:06.639
So yeah, so this is an interesting one, because Ning just mentioned we'll come back in a year

00:54:07.520 --> 00:54:09.840
and we'll tell you success stories.

00:54:09.840 --> 00:54:12.239
So some of this is work in progress.

00:54:12.239 --> 00:54:15.840
These are things we're trying out right now, and we haven't got too much experience of

00:54:15.840 --> 00:54:16.560
doing it.

00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:22.080
So this is our intention, and we have some early teams that are trying out storing in

00:54:22.080 --> 00:54:22.959
Parquet.

00:54:22.959 --> 00:54:24.879
And so far, that's working really well.

00:54:25.919 --> 00:54:29.919
There's obviously going to be a tension when you're storing things in Parquet or in SAS

00:54:29.919 --> 00:54:32.399
7 BDAT, because you've got to get SAS to be able to read that files.

00:54:32.399 --> 00:54:35.199
But we're building solutions for that to be able to happen.

00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:42.159
But I mean, at least for natively using them in R, we're quite optimistic about it, because

00:54:42.159 --> 00:54:44.399
Parquet is a really efficient format.

00:54:44.399 --> 00:54:48.719
And just in our testing, it seems to be that it's going to be a really good format for

00:54:49.679 --> 00:54:55.120
not only for R, but also if we use Python, Python can read Parquet natively as well.

00:54:55.120 --> 00:54:55.620
Yeah.

00:54:56.800 --> 00:54:57.600
Fantastic.

00:54:57.600 --> 00:54:58.719
Any other comments on that one?

00:55:00.800 --> 00:55:05.120
Maybe that's not related to this particular question, but somehow there was a question

00:55:05.760 --> 00:55:10.080
around whether in the end we still have to submit these XPT files, which is a SAS format

00:55:10.080 --> 00:55:11.120
to the FDA.

00:55:11.120 --> 00:55:12.800
And actually, indeed, that's the case.

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:15.760
So this is something we use internally for data storage.

00:55:15.760 --> 00:55:21.600
And once the data makes it to the FDA, we'll use XPT, or maybe if the FDA approves this

00:55:21.600 --> 00:55:24.560
new format, which is being proposed, data set JSON.

00:55:26.159 --> 00:55:26.959
Fantastic.

00:55:26.959 --> 00:55:27.280
All right.

00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:29.360
Let's move on to question two.

00:55:29.360 --> 00:55:33.520
Can you speak more about the capabilities Shiny offers that you did not have?

00:55:36.080 --> 00:55:37.600
Oh, very open-ended.

00:55:38.479 --> 00:55:44.159
I think really one key aspect for us was around this reproducibility I mentioned.

00:55:44.959 --> 00:55:48.479
Because, for example, Tableau or Spotfire are stuff that we use internally.

00:55:48.479 --> 00:55:51.679
It's certainly very powerful, and you can do lots of stuff.

00:55:51.679 --> 00:55:56.159
But if a safety scientist has such a dashboard and comes with you, this is something I want

00:55:56.159 --> 00:55:57.280
to have in my CSR.

00:55:57.280 --> 00:56:00.879
You have basically no idea how they reach to that conclusion.

00:56:00.879 --> 00:56:03.360
Which subgroup is this that you see on this plot?

00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:06.000
How did they fill the networks, events, et cetera?

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:09.040
So that really was, for us, a big push.

00:56:09.040 --> 00:56:14.800
And also, we wanted to have something which bridges this gap between the regulatory side

00:56:14.800 --> 00:56:18.239
of things, or classical tables, and the exploratory nature.

00:56:18.239 --> 00:56:22.639
So a demographic table I showed you basically looks the same in the app as it would in the

00:56:22.639 --> 00:56:23.760
final CSR.

00:56:23.760 --> 00:56:26.000
And thereby, it's really a nice match between those two.

00:56:26.879 --> 00:56:27.280
Got it.

00:56:28.320 --> 00:56:28.879
Awesome.

00:56:28.879 --> 00:56:30.320
Any other comments on that one?

00:56:31.199 --> 00:56:36.320
Oh, and maybe just to add, so for example, I'm not sure how much statistical analysis

00:56:36.320 --> 00:56:38.479
functionality Tableau or Spotfire have.

00:56:38.479 --> 00:56:40.639
They're mostly for visualizing data.

00:56:40.639 --> 00:56:45.360
But for example, in Teal, you can fit an MRMM model, which is something fairly complex.

00:56:45.360 --> 00:56:49.760
And I'm not sure, besides SAS and R, which other languages even can do that.

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:54.399
And certainly, I don't think any dashboard app out there has the capability.

00:56:55.280 --> 00:56:55.919
Right, right.

00:56:56.560 --> 00:56:57.040
Awesome.

00:56:57.040 --> 00:56:58.959
Let's move to question three.

00:56:58.959 --> 00:57:05.120
Is there a balance of using Python and R in your strategy, or a wholesale decision for

00:57:05.120 --> 00:57:05.840
R?

00:57:05.840 --> 00:57:07.760
If the latter, how is that made?

00:57:09.520 --> 00:57:15.280
So I think the way to look about it is the backbone of our data science is going to be

00:57:15.280 --> 00:57:15.520
R.

00:57:15.520 --> 00:57:19.679
So our focus of developing tools is going to be R.

00:57:19.679 --> 00:57:23.199
So when we look at our resource of our actual teams, building the tools that we're going

00:57:23.199 --> 00:57:24.639
to use, that's going to be in R.

00:57:24.639 --> 00:57:28.399
And that's kind of the natural outstretch of that is that most teams are going to be

00:57:28.399 --> 00:57:30.560
using R because that's what the tools have been building.

00:57:31.199 --> 00:57:36.320
But there will be the ability to use Python where the problem is more easily solved in

00:57:36.320 --> 00:57:36.800
Python.

00:57:38.239 --> 00:57:43.840
As to why R, I don't know if I want to say anything too controversial about the difference

00:57:43.840 --> 00:57:45.120
between R and Python.

00:57:45.120 --> 00:57:51.760
But I think it's fair to say that as a statistical piece of software in the open source, I would

00:57:51.760 --> 00:57:57.360
argue that it is at least equivalent with Python when it comes to statistical problems.

00:57:58.159 --> 00:58:02.080
And there's a lot of benefits in terms of just like what our talent base knew already.

00:58:02.879 --> 00:58:05.360
Yeah, I don't know if anyone else wanted to say anything else about it.

00:58:06.320 --> 00:58:07.280
Yeah, I totally agree.

00:58:07.280 --> 00:58:11.840
I feel like right now, probably in academia for advanced statistical methodologies, like

00:58:11.840 --> 00:58:14.239
many of them are still developing in R.

00:58:14.239 --> 00:58:17.199
And yeah, for example, MMRM, et cetera.

00:58:17.199 --> 00:58:17.439
Yeah.

00:58:17.439 --> 00:58:22.000
So I think like right now, there's more tools available in R for some of the statistical

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:22.399
methods.

00:58:23.679 --> 00:58:24.080
Got it.

00:58:25.040 --> 00:58:25.600
All right.

00:58:25.600 --> 00:58:28.399
Going to move to a popular question that comes up quite a bit.

00:58:28.399 --> 00:58:33.760
What kind of validation is required for using R, Python for clinical trials reporting?

00:58:37.439 --> 00:58:42.000
So yeah, I think Thomas mentioned already the auto-validate tool.

00:58:42.719 --> 00:58:47.360
But I should say that that comes from a history of collaboration across the industry.

00:58:48.239 --> 00:58:56.159
So there was still going the R validation hub group, which I think is still led by Andy

00:58:56.159 --> 00:58:56.560
Nichols.

00:58:57.280 --> 00:59:05.120
It was initially anyway, which looked at these kind of questions as to what is R validated?

00:59:05.120 --> 00:59:08.159
How do you validate an R package and those kind of questions from it?

00:59:09.040 --> 00:59:15.600
So it was kind of a collaboration, taking the sort of outcomes from that and building

00:59:15.600 --> 00:59:20.239
those into our internal solutions, working with our internal validation teams to get

00:59:20.239 --> 00:59:21.040
consensus.

00:59:21.840 --> 00:59:27.760
And yeah, the auto-validate R was a real late forward for us because it was an in-house

00:59:27.760 --> 00:59:33.040
solution for validating R packages really quickly, effectively, automatically.

00:59:33.040 --> 00:59:38.080
That's why it's called autovalidate, in that we have these standard measures of an R package

00:59:38.080 --> 00:59:42.159
quality that we can use to assess whether we think an R package can be included.

00:59:42.879 --> 00:59:45.760
And I mean, if it doesn't meet those standards, then we have to do some action.

00:59:45.760 --> 00:59:50.239
But if we get an R package and it meets all those standards, then it can be included in

00:59:50.239 --> 00:59:54.639
our suite of packages kind of straight away, which was a real leap forward for us.

00:59:55.520 --> 00:59:57.360
All right, we're almost at the hour here.

00:59:57.360 --> 01:00:01.120
So we're going to go a little fast on these next two, but let's squeeze them in if we

01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:01.360
can.

01:00:02.080 --> 01:00:07.439
The next one is how much manual work do you have with this approach between raw data and

01:00:07.439 --> 01:00:08.879
STDM and Atom?

01:00:08.879 --> 01:00:16.879
So the piece from raw data to STDM, as I mentioned, we are getting around 80% or so

01:00:16.879 --> 01:00:20.080
automated, which means you only have to take care of the manual 20%.

01:00:20.879 --> 01:00:25.040
You would go into this Mint app and then basically say, OK, this is how I want to map

01:00:25.040 --> 01:00:27.120
this raw data into this standard.

01:00:27.120 --> 01:00:30.320
And if you have done it for one study, you can actually then reuse it again for the next

01:00:30.320 --> 01:00:32.479
step, thereby again gaining efficiency.

01:00:32.479 --> 01:00:34.959
So this should be really fairly streamlined.

01:00:35.760 --> 01:00:40.560
Then the next step from STDM to Atom, that's much more difficult because it's not just

01:00:40.560 --> 01:00:41.439
a simple mapping.

01:00:41.439 --> 01:00:46.320
Depending on the analysis you want to perform downstream, you need to derive certain things.

01:00:46.320 --> 01:00:50.719
So while we have template code available that implements sort of our general standards,

01:00:50.719 --> 01:00:52.479
there will always have to be extensions.

01:00:52.479 --> 01:00:56.159
And this will be a much larger part of the work compared to STDM.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:00:59.840
All right, anything else on that one?

01:01:01.840 --> 01:01:03.840
Two more questions we'll knock out here pretty quick.

01:01:04.399 --> 01:01:06.239
All right, question six here.

01:01:06.239 --> 01:01:11.840
Do you keep the datasets under version control in GitLab, et cetera, along with the code?

01:01:11.840 --> 01:01:14.159
If so, do you have issues with large data files?

01:01:14.959 --> 01:01:16.639
We can just say no, no, we don't.

01:01:17.919 --> 01:01:23.120
So we have a separate solution, which I think Thomas mentioned, using S3 for storing our

01:01:23.120 --> 01:01:23.439
data.

01:01:24.879 --> 01:01:30.560
Yeah, I think it's fair to say if we did store on GitLab, yes, we would have a lot of trouble.

01:01:31.040 --> 01:01:33.199
All right.

01:01:33.199 --> 01:01:39.120
Will the Roche ecosystem of apps work with the Pharmaverse suite, or is it one ecosystem

01:01:39.120 --> 01:01:39.919
versus the other?

01:01:42.639 --> 01:01:43.919
It's an interesting way to put it.

01:01:43.919 --> 01:01:48.959
So more or less everything I talked about is actually part of the Pharmaverse.

01:01:48.959 --> 01:01:55.360
And the Pharmaverse is, you don't have to think about it as kind of us putting it out

01:01:55.360 --> 01:01:55.520
there.

01:01:55.520 --> 01:01:58.159
There's lots of companies contributing various stuff.

01:01:58.159 --> 01:02:01.760
There's actually our tables, for example, is part of it, but there's other table packages

01:02:01.760 --> 01:02:02.560
as well.

01:02:02.560 --> 01:02:06.879
So it's just kind of a curated list of packages that adhere to a certain set of standards

01:02:07.760 --> 01:02:09.600
and that are useful for clinical reporting.

01:02:10.639 --> 01:02:15.280
And most of them work independently of each other, so you can mix and match whatever you

01:02:15.280 --> 01:02:16.879
want to use.

01:02:16.879 --> 01:02:22.560
And I don't really think there is like a Roche kind of app suite, kind of just the Pharmaverse

01:02:22.560 --> 01:02:25.840
out there, and we're using as much as possible out of that.

01:02:26.719 --> 01:02:29.919
I think we got one more question here that was quite popular.

01:02:29.919 --> 01:02:31.840
There was one that came in about Parquet.

01:02:31.840 --> 01:02:33.520
I think we got to that one, so I'm going to skip it.

01:02:33.520 --> 01:02:38.719
But the next one is, can you please elaborate on the auto-validate for packages?

01:02:38.719 --> 01:02:40.239
I think there was some interest on that.

01:02:42.080 --> 01:02:50.719
OK, so I think, yeah, so the basic idea is it's a tool that can generate reports, the

01:02:50.719 --> 01:02:53.840
kind of standard reports we need for validation.

01:02:53.840 --> 01:02:57.760
So those are generated by the tool.

01:02:57.760 --> 01:03:02.560
And what you do as a user, as a creator of an R package, is you submit your R package

01:03:02.560 --> 01:03:05.120
and you make sure it meets a sufficient quality check.

01:03:05.120 --> 01:03:07.600
So we have a list of different quality checks that it does.

01:03:08.159 --> 01:03:11.840
I don't know off the top of my head what they all are, but they include things like obviously

01:03:11.840 --> 01:03:17.120
passing CRAN checks, having test coverage past a certain level, you know, all these

01:03:17.120 --> 01:03:23.600
kind of sensible things that we think denote an R package being of sufficient quality.

01:03:23.600 --> 01:03:27.520
And if you pass those, then auto-validate does the rest of the work for you.

01:03:29.760 --> 01:03:33.600
And there was a great talk by our colleagues at R Informer just on this topic, I think

01:03:33.600 --> 01:03:34.399
like 20 minutes.

01:03:34.399 --> 01:03:36.719
So if that's of interest to you, definitely check that out.

01:03:37.280 --> 01:03:41.679
Yeah, and you can get that talk and others on the R Informer YouTube channel.

01:03:42.479 --> 01:03:46.000
I think with that, I'm going to thank all of you for such wonderful information.

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:49.600
I know there's a lot of excitement about the webinar, Thomas, that you mentioned that's

01:03:49.600 --> 01:03:50.080
coming up.

01:03:50.080 --> 01:03:51.520
I think they can get that.

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:53.679
Is that through the R Consortium webinar series?

01:03:53.679 --> 01:03:54.320
Yes, it is.

01:03:54.320 --> 01:03:56.639
And it's not yet on the website, unfortunately.

01:03:56.639 --> 01:03:59.040
But February 24th is the date.

01:03:59.040 --> 01:03:59.540
Teaser.

01:04:00.959 --> 01:04:01.280
All right.

01:04:01.280 --> 01:04:01.600
Yep.

01:04:01.600 --> 01:04:02.639
Keep an eye out for that.

01:04:02.639 --> 01:04:04.719
And with that, I will wrap it up.

01:04:04.719 --> 01:04:06.639
Thanks for all the great questions and comments.

01:04:06.639 --> 01:04:08.239
It's great to see the community come out.

01:04:08.800 --> 01:04:11.919
Thanks again for all the effort and time to put this together, especially right after

01:04:11.919 --> 01:04:12.959
the holidays.

01:04:12.959 --> 01:04:17.840
And with that, I'll wish everyone farewell and have a great day, morning, evening, where

01:04:17.840 --> 01:04:18.399
you are.

01:04:18.399 --> 01:04:18.899
Thanks a lot.

